<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/ed97154f7d1d1efe3a90b1b92de74ac0> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Male figure; Haida; early 1840s\r\nWood, argillite, bone; h. 26 cm.\r\nRMV 2845-10; museum purchase, Berkeley Galleries, London 1950\r\n\r\nThis figure is unusual in that its body is made of wood painted black as if to simulate argillite whereas its head is argillite with elaborate wavy hair and mutton-chop sideburns, and its aquiline face is white-colored, bone or ivory. The arms and large, oversize hands extend well forward of the body. The figure is depicted wearing a nautical, visored hat, a heavy great coat with detailed seams, cuffs and pockets, and large boots with prominent heels and soles The clothing worn by this figure is very similar to that depicted in an oil painting of William Rich (b. 1800) who was one of the botanists on the U.S. Exploring Expedition of 1838-42. Rich is shown wearing a visored cap, a coat with a pronounced collar and lapel, a shirt with an upright collar extending up past the collar of the coat, and a large knotted neck scarf (Viola and Margolis 1985:30).\r\n\r\nA survey of the published literature and on-line collections has not resulted in the discovery of a similar piece. A carved bone Euro-American figure sitting on a wooden chair and identified as a “sea captain” is in the Southwest Museum of the American Indian (Inveriarty 1950:Fig. 183). There are a number of composite figures in other museum collections but none with wooden bodies. These include a seated argillite figure with an ivory face holding an open book while sitting on a wooden chair (Holm 1982:141), at least six standing figures with white ivory or stone faces (Gunther 1962:23; Drew and Wilson 1980:191; Viola and Margolis 1985:4; Brown 1995:150-191), a standing Euro-American figure with a “red” argillite head and a second standing figure with a “red” argillite face (Holm 1982:140, 142). Of the six standing figures two are a joined pair of figures (New York State Historical Association #T0187, and ex-Peabody Harvard piece). There are also at least three of these figures with replacement heads or faces of ivory (Macnair & Hoover 2002:57,60).\r\n\r\nIt is also unusual because most of these Euro-American figures are standing, not seated. Only two seated figures were identified (Holm 1982:141; Macnair and Hoover 2002:57). Here the figure is seated on an unpainted wooden chair. The pre-eminent art historian Bill Holm suggests that the rarity of seated argillite figures may be a consequence of the difficulty of quarrying a large enough block of argillite to produce such a thick sculpture (Holm 1982:141). Perhaps this also explains the choice of easily obtainable wood over difficult to acquire argillite. \r\n\r\nAlthough there are no other wooden figures of men dressed in Euro-American clothing contemporary with the argillite figures, there is a wonderful wooden carved figure of a First Nations’ woman with braided hair and wearing Western clothing that is attributed as Haida in origin (AIAM 1982:1). There are however two elaborate carvings of Euro-Americans in the form of pipes that were probably carved at the same time as the Euro-American argillite figures (Holm 1982:132-133). Other wooden carvings of male and female figures wearing blankets are illustrated in the literature and are attributed as Haida in origin. However there is little documentation associated with these artifacts to confirm their ethnic origin (Coe 1976:142-143). The Haida were not the only Northwest Coast group that produced carvings of Euro-American sailors for sale to newcomers. There is at least one illustrated wooden carving of a sailor collected at the mouth of the Columbia River by S.B. Elliot of the U.S. Exploring Expedition on the Oregon coast in 1841. The figure is more rudimentary than the Haida Euro-American figures, perhaps reflecting a more abstract Chinook aesthetic. The sailor is standing with his hands thrust into trouser pockets and wearing a tam-like sailor’s hat (Gilman 2003:310, 389). The presence of these portraits of Euro-Americans and the adoption of other aspects of Euro-American culture indicate the fascination that First Nations peoples had for the exotic technology and customs of the newcomers. Another illustrative example are carvings of Russian Orthodox priests on totem poles (Wright 2001a:204).\r\n\r\nAlan Hoover\r\nRoyal British Columbia Museum, Victoria; 2015\r\n\r\n\r\nSteven C. Brown, The Spirit Within: Northwest Coast Native Art from the John H. Hauberg Collection; Seattle Art Museum; Seattle, 1995. Ralph T. Coe, Sacred Circles: 2000 Years of North American Indian Art; Arts Council of Great Britain; London, 1976. Leslie Drew and Douglas Wilson, Argillite: Art of the Haida; Hancock House; Vancouver, 1980. Carolyn Gilman, Lewis and Clark: Across the Divide; Smithsonian Institution; Washington, DC, 2003. Erna Gunther, Northwest Coast Indian Art; Century 21 Exposition; Seattle, 1962. Bill Holm, Objects of Unique Artistry; in: Thomas Vaughan and Bill Holm, Soft Gold: The Fur Trade and Cultural Exchange on the Northwest Coast of America:31-167; Oregon Historical Society; Portland, 1982. Robert B. Inveriarty, Art of the Northwest Coast Indians; University of California Press; Berkeley, 1950. Peter L. Macnair and Alan L. Hoover, The Magic Leaves: A History of Argillite Carving; Royal BC Museum; Victoria, 2002 (orig. ed, 1984). Herman J. Viola and Carolyn Margolis, Magnificent Voyagers: The U.S. Exploring Expedition, 1838-1842; Smithsonian Institution Press; Washington, D.C., 1985. Robin K. Wright, Northern Haida Master Carvers; University of Washington Press; Seattle, 2001.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nArgillite zeemansfiguurtje\r\n\r\nArgillite is een soort leisteen, een glanzend en zacht materiaal dat bewerkt kan worden met houtsnijwerktuigen. Het wordt aan de Noordwest kust alleen gevonden op de Queen Charlotte Islands voor de noordelijke kust van British Columbia (Holm 1983:104). Soms werden naast leisteen tevens andere materialen gebruikt, zoals been, ivoor of rode leisteen (Holm 1983:107).\r\n\r\nLeistenen figuren zoals deze zijn gemaakt door Haida Indianen voor de verkoop aan zeelieden, handelaren, missionarissen, antropologen en toeristen. Dit gebeurde vanaf het begin van de negentiende eeuw tot op heden (Holm 1983:104). Lange tijd werden leistenen producten niet interessant gevonden door etnologische verzamelaars, vanwege het gebrek aan authenticiteit: zij waren niet traditioneel, zij werden voor blanken gemaakt en vertegenwoordigden daarom blanke ideeën. Tegenwoordig is de houding van conservatoren veranderd en worden deze voorwerpen en privé-verzamelingen door musea aangekocht, onderzocht en tentoongesteld (Cole 1985:292-3).\r\n\r\nDit zeemansfiguurtje is grotendeels van hout; de mensenfiguur is zwart geschilderd zodat dit op argillite lijkt. De pet en het haar zijn van argillite, het gezicht van been.\r\n\r\nDe voorstellingen van de beeldjes lijken vaak op portretten en zijn dat waarschijnlijk ook geweest. Scheepsofficieren en handelaren vonden het blijkbaar leuk om een dergelijk portret in de vorm van een beeldje van henzelf of hun vrouw te hebben. Sommige vrouwenafbeeldingen hebben een Haida uiterlijk en dragen Europese kleding, wat kan wijzen op huwelijken tussen Haida en bijvoorbeeld Europese handelaren die een tijd aan de Noordwestkust verbleven. De zeemansbeeldjes staan meestal stevig op hun beide voeten, met hun handen in hun zakken. Details zoals kledingzomen, knopen en schoenzolen werden vaak uitvergroot door de hierdoor gefascineerde Haida beeldhouwers. Voor de Haida exotische Kaukasische trekken zoals lange smalle gezichten, een prominente neus en smalle lippen werden ook uitvergroot (Holm 1987:160).\r\n\r\nVoor de toeristenmakrkt worden veel miniaturen gemaakt uit argillite. Vooral miniatuur totempaaltjes zijn erg populair. Inmiddels worden dit soort objecten ook in zwarte kunststof nagemaakt.\r\n\r\nLiteratuur:\r\n\r\nCole, Douglas\r\nCaptured Heritage. The Scramble for Northwest Coast Artifacts.\r\nUniversity of Washington Press, Seattle & London, 1985.\r\n\r\nHolm, Bill\r\nThe Box of Daylight. Northwest Coast Indian Art.\r\nSeattle Art Museum. University of Washington Press, Seattle & London, 1983.\r\n\r\nHolm, Bill\r\nSpirit and Ancestor. A Century of Northwest Coast Indian Art at the Burke Museum.\r\nUniversity of Washington Press, Seattle & London, 1987." .
